### Lifetime Elision in Rust

Rust has rules that allow omitting lifetime annotations in certain common patterns. The compiler infers lifetimes automatically.

---

### Elision Rules

| Rule | Description |
|------|-------------|
| Each input reference gets its own lifetime | `&T` becomes `&'_ T` |
| If exactly one input lifetime, it's assigned to all outputs | `fn f(x: &T) -> &U` becomes `fn f<'a>(x: &'a T) -> &'a U` |
| If `&self` or `&mut self`, its lifetime is assigned to all outputs | Methods follow this rule |

---

### Examples

```rust
// Elided: compiler adds lifetimes automatically
fn first_word(s: &str) -> &str {
    s.split_whitespace().next().unwrap()
}

// Desugared: what the compiler sees
fn first_word<'a>(s: &'a str) -> &'a str {
    s.split_whitespace().next().unwrap()
}

// Multiple inputs require explicit annotations
fn longest(x: &str, y: &str) -> &str {  // ERROR!
    if x.len() > y.len() { x } else { y }
}

// Must write explicitly:
fn longest<'a>(x: &'a str, y: &'a str) -> &'a str { ... }
```

> **Key Point:** You never need to write lifetime annotations for simple functions with one input reference. The compiler's elision rules handle the common cases automatically, reducing noise while maintaining safety.

codeExample:
fn main() {
    let s = String::from("hello world");
    let word = first_word(&s);  // lifetimes elided
    println!("First word: {}", word);
}

// Lifetime elision handles this automatically
fn first_word(s: &str) -> &str {
    match s.find(' ') {
        Some(pos) => &s[..pos],
        None => s,
    }
}
